 updated and expanded paperback edition gives newly uncovered details about the policies that engage clinicians in torture. It discusses the ongoing furor over psychologists' participating in interrogations. Most explosively this new edition shows how interrogation psychologists may have moved from information-gathering to coercive experiments, warning all of us about a new direction in U.S. policy and military medicine—a direction that not so long ago was unthinkable.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aHealth Policy. 4aMedical. 7aMEDICAL / Health Policy.2bisacsh1 aMiles M.D., Steven H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025968340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094398840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520943988423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520943988/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles